# Java

## Core
- Target Java 21. Use records for immutable data models, sealed classes where
  appropriate, and modern idioms (switch expressions, text blocks, etc.).
- Never return null — use `Optional` from repository and service methods.
- All configuration (table names, bucket names, region) comes from environment
  variables. Never hardcode these.
- Use SLF4J for logging everywhere. No `System.out.println`.
- All external HTTP calls must have a connect timeout of 5s, a read timeout of
  10s, and retry with exponential backoff (max 3 attempts, starting at 500ms).
- Keep Lambda handlers thin — business logic lives in service and scoring classes,
  not in the handler itself.
- No commented-out code. No dead imports.
- Constructor injection only — no field injection, no setter injection.

## Naming & Readability
- Names should be self-documenting. Never abbreviate — `playerGameStats` not `pgs`,
  `calculateEdgeScore` not `calcEdge`.
- Boolean variables and methods should read as questions: `isHomeGame`, `hasMinimumSampleSize`.
- Avoid generic names like `data`, `result`, `temp`, `obj`.
- Methods should do one thing. If you need "and" to describe what a method does, split it.
- Avoid deep nesting — prefer early returns and guard clauses.

## Design
- Program to interfaces, not implementations. Depend on `EdgeScorer` not `PointsEdgeScorer`.
- Use the builder pattern for objects with more than 3-4 constructor parameters.
- Validate inputs at the entry point of a method (fail fast). Don't let bad data
  travel deep into the call stack before blowing up.
- Prefer composition over inheritance, but use inheritance when it genuinely makes sense.
- No magic numbers or strings inline — everything goes in constants.

## Immutability
- Prefer immutable objects. Use Java records for data carriers. Never expose
  mutable internal state.
- Collections returned from methods should be unmodifiable (`List.copyOf`,
  `Collections.unmodifiableList`) unless the caller genuinely needs to mutate them.
- Use `final` on fields that are set once (constructor-injected dependencies,
  constants). Use `final` on local variables when the value never reassigns.

## Exception Handling & Logging
- Never swallow exceptions silently. Either handle meaningfully, log and rethrow,
  or wrap in a domain-specific unchecked exception.
- Log exceptions with full stack traces at ERROR level. Log key decision points
  at DEBUG level. Do not log sensitive data.
